%I A397059 #5 Jun 18 2026 19:52:18
%S A397059 1,2,4,14,51,230,1084,5456,27975,146442,774514
%N A397059 Number of free polyplets (king-move connected sets of n cells on the square grid, adjacent if they share an edge or a corner) whose king-adjacency graph is a tree.
%C A397059 A polyplet (or polyking) is a cluster of unit cells on the square grid that a chess king could traverse: cells count as joined when they share an edge or only touch at a corner (8-connectivity).
%C A397059 Its king-adjacency graph puts one vertex in each cell and an edge between every touching pair. a(n) counts the free polyplets on n cells, up to the square's rotations and reflections, whose graph is a tree -- connected and acyclic, with exactly n-1 adjacencies.
%C A397059 A connected n-cell polyplet has at least n-1 adjacencies, with equality only for a tree, so a(n) counts the sparsest king-connected shapes -- the acyclic ones, where every adjacency is essential. The tree fraction of all polyplets (A030222) shrinks as n grows.
%C A397059 This is the king analog of A131482, which uses rook (edge-only) adjacency. Neither family contains the other: the diagonal pair is a king-tree but not rook-connected (so a(2)=2 against one rook-tree), while an L-tromino is a rook-tree whose corner contact makes its king graph a 3-cycle.
%C A397059 Conjecture: a(n) grows at the same exponential rate as A030222, the tree restriction affecting only the sub-exponential factor (UNVERIFIED).
%H A397059 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A397059">Paper and figures</a>, GitHub.
%Y A397059 Cf. A006770 (number of fixed n-celled polyplets), A030222 (number of free n-polyplets; the base family filtered here), A030233 (number of one-sided n-polyplets), A131482 (free polyominoes whose rook, edge-only adjacency graph is a tree; the 4-connected analog).
%K A397059 nonn,more,hard
